'''"Por Debajo de la Mesa"''' ("Underneath the Table") is a song written by [[Armando Manzanero]]  and performed by Mexican recording artist [[Luis Miguel]]. Arranged by [[Bebu Silvetti]], it was one of the two original compositions written for Miguel's fifteenth studio album ''[[Romances]]''. It was released as the lead single from the album on July 15, 1997 and it became his thirteenth number-one single on the [[Hot Latin Songs|''Billboard'' Hot Latin Songs]] chart in the United States. The music video features Miguel performing at a fine-dining restaurant in [[New York City]].

The track received a negative reaction from [[Achy Obejas]] of the ''[[Chicago Tribune]]'' who called it "lame". It was nominated [[Lo Nuestro Award for Pop Song of the Year|Pop Song of the Year]] at the [[Premio Lo Nuestro 1998|10th Annual Lo Nuestro Awards]] and Manzanero was awarded a [[Broadcast Music, Inc.]] (BMI) Latin Award for writing the song. Manzanero performed the record as a duet with several artists such as [[Tania Libertad]] and [[Susana Zabaleta]].

== Background ==
In 1991 Miguel released ''[[Romance (Luis Miguel album)|Romance]]'', a collection of classic Latin ballads, the oldest of which dates back to the 1940s. The album was [[music producer|produced]] by Armando Manzanero and arranged by Bebu Silvetti,<ref name="romance">{{cite web|title=Romance&nbsp;<U+2014> Credits|url=http://allmusic.com/album/romance-r100917/credits|accessdate=2011-04-01|work=Allmusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref> and was credited for revitalizing the [[bolero]] genre.<ref name="popculture">{{cite book|first1 = Cordelia|last1 = Candelaria| first2 = Peter|last2 = Garcia| first3 = Arturo|last3 =Adalma| volume = 2| title = Encyclopedia of Latino popular culture| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=3uD6PKXl3q4C&lpg=PA552&dq=%22world%20music%22%20awards%20%22luis%20miguel%22%20%22romances%22&pg=PA551#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate = 2011-03-14| year = 2004| publisher = Greenwood Publishing Group| location = Westport, United States| isbn = 9780313322150| pages = 551<U+2013>552}}</ref> It also made history as the first Spanish-language album to be certified gold by the [[Recording Industry Association of America]] (RIAA) in the United States.<ref name="latinoise">{{cite web
|title= Luis Miguel
|url=http://www.latinoise.com/Luis_Miguel.html
|publisher=Latinoise
|accessdate=2011-02-19}}</ref> A follow-up to ''Romance'' was released in 1994 under the title ''[[Segundo Romance]]'' (''Second Romance''), which was produced by Miguel, Juan Carlos Calder<U+00F3>n and Kiko Cibrian.<ref name="segundoromance">{{cite web|title=Segundo Romance&nbsp;<U+2014> Credits|url=http://allmusic.com/album/segundo-romance-r203611|accessdate=2011-04-01|work=Allmusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref> Both albums received a platinum certification by the RIAA in the United States and also became successful in countries outside of Latin America and the United States, such as [[Finland]] and [[Saudi Arabia]],<ref name="growsup"/> selling over twelve million copies combined.<ref name="growsup">{{cite web
| last = Obejas
| first = Achy
| date = 1996-08-30
|title= Luis Miguel Grows Up And Moves On With His Latest Albums
|url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1996-08-30/entertainment/9608300302_1_luis-miguel-nada-es-igual-aries
|work=Chicago Tribune
|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]
|accessdate=2011-02-19}}</ref>{{Certification Cite Ref|region=United States|artist=Luis Miguel|accessdate=2011-02-19}}<ref>{{cite journal|year= 1997|journal= [[Forbes]]|volume= 160|issue=5<U+2013>9 |page=155|last=La Franco|first= Robert|publisher= Forbes Inc.}}</ref>

In December 1996 Miguel held a press conference in [[Buenos Aires]], [[Argentina]], where he announced his desire to record a third ''Romance'' album and mentioned the possibility of working with Manzanero and [[Juan Gabriel]]. He also expressed an interest in singing in Italian and Portuguese,<ref>{{cite news |title=Va por el tercero|newspaper=[[Reforma]]|url=http://busquedas.gruporeforma.com/reforma/Pages/BuscaImpresa.aspx|publisher=[[Grupo Reforma]]|trans_title=Going for third|date= 1996-12-10|language=Spanish|accessdate=2011-04-09}}{{subscription required}}</ref> although the album's songs are originally all in Spanish. Two months later Manzanero confirmed that he was working with Miguel on another bolero-inspired ballads album, under the tentative title ''Tercer Romance'' ("Third Romance").<ref name="feb1997">
{{cite journal| last = Lannert| first = John| date = 1997-02-08| title = Latin Notas| journal = Billboard| publisher = Nielsen Business Media, Inc.| volume = 109| issue = 6| page = 32| url = http://books.google.com/books?id=wA4EAAAAMBAJ&lpg=PA31&dq=%22luis%20miguel%22%20intitle%3Abillboard&pg=PA32#v=onepage&q&f=false |accessdate = 2011-03-28}}</ref> Miguel's record label confirmed that fourteen tracks would be included on the album under the title ''Romances''.<ref>{{cite news |title= Es Luis Miguel un clasico del romance|first=Ang<U+00E9>lica |last= De Le<U+00F3>n|newspaper=Reforma|url=http://busquedas.gruporeforma.com/reforma/Pages/BuscaImpresa.aspx|publisher=Grupo Reforma|trans_title=Is Luis Miguel romantic classic|date= 1997-07-16|language=Spanish|accessdate=2011-03-28}}{{subscription required}}</ref> "Por Debajo de la Mesa" was written by Manzanero as one of the two original compositions for the album along with "Contigo (Estar Contigo)".<ref name="Romances">{{cite web|title=Romances&nbsp;<U+2014> Credits|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/romances-r308222/credits|accessdate=2011-02-19|work=Allmusic|publisher=Rovi Corporation}}</ref>

